Allegory and Symbolism
> Later, Goethe explains the difference between himself and Schiller in terms of the relationship between "allegory" and "symbol" as follows. There is a great difference between a poet who seeks the particular for the universal, as [Schiller] does, and one who sees the universal in the particular, as [Goethe] does. From the former approach arises [allegory], in which the particular becomes a mere instance or example of the universal. The latter, on the other hand, is truly the essence of literature (Poesie), and it expresses a [particular] without recalling or directing the universal. Now, he who vividly perceives this particular, without realizing it or only later, has at the same time acquired the [universal]."(MR27) It is clear that the latter is what is called by Goethe "[the symbolic]"
