　I know some of you may not be familiar with the phrase, "winning the universal."
　When you have a new experience Y, you realize, "Oh, this is similar to an experience X that I had before," and [analogy] produces knowledge that can be applied to experience Y, you know a posteriori that you "had universal knowledge that crosses experience X and experience Y".
　　Whether this universal knowledge is verbalized or not is immaterial.

I've painted a few pictures related to [rootless knowledge], but maybe it's not a good idea to paint abstract concepts in the same circle as concrete experiences. Universal knowledge = abstract concepts are not always clearly verbalized at the time of application to new experiences.
